        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-brand-600 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">Blog</p>
        <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-extrabold text-slate-900 tracking-tight leading-tight">
          Construction Daily Report: What to Include (+ Template)
        </h1>
        <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-slate-400">Published July 24, 2026 · 7 min read</p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-headings:font-semibold prose-headings:tracking-tight prose-a:text-brand-600"
      >
        <p>
          A delay claim shows up four months after a pour. The GC asks who was on site on a Thursday
          in March and what work actually got done that day. If you wrote it down that Thursday, you
          have an answer. If you didn't, you have an argument — and arguments without records tend
          to go the wrong way.
        </p>
        <p>
          Construction daily reports exist for exactly that moment. This guide covers what goes in a
          daily report, how to structure it like a template your crew can fill out consistently, and
          why the fields that feel optional are usually the ones you need most in a dispute.
        </p>

        <div class="rounded-xl bg-slate-50 border border-slate-100 p-6 not-prose my-8">
          <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-3">Key takeaways</h2>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-slate-600 list-disc pl-5">
            <li>
              Record the project, date, and personnel on site every day — these three fields are
              non-negotiable.
            </li>
            <li>
              The detail section captures work performed, materials received, visitors on site, and
              issues.
            </li>
            <li>
              Tag each entry (Progress, Issue, Delay, Safety, Delivery, Inspection) so you can
              filter by type months later.
            </li>
            <li>Photos attached to the log tie a visual record to the exact date and project.</li>
            <li>
              A report written the same day carries far more evidentiary weight than one
              reconstructed after the fact.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h2>What is a construction daily report?</h2>
        <p>
          A construction daily report — also called a site log, daily log, or field report — is a
          dated entry for a specific project that captures what happened on the jobsite that day.
          Who was there, what got done, what came in, who visited, what went wrong.
        </p>
        <p>
          The format matters less than the consistency and timing. A daily report written the day it
          happened is contemporaneous evidence. That's what makes it valuable when a delay claim,
          payment dispute, or safety question arises months or years later — the record predates the
          dispute, so it can't look like it was manufactured to win an argument.
        </p>
        <p>
          In BuildWorkPro, <a href="/features/site-logs/">site logs</a> are the daily report module. Each
          entry is tied to a project and a date (defaulting to today), so the structure is already there
          — you fill it in rather than inventing a format from scratch.
        </p>

        <h2>What a construction daily report template should include</h2>
        <p>
          Think of a daily report as two layers: the header fields you fill in when you create the
          entry, and the detail fields you complete once the entry exists. Together they tell the
          full story of the day.
        </p>

        <h2>Header fields (create the entry)</h2>
        <p>
          These four fields go in when you open a new log entry. They should take under a minute.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Project.</strong> Which job this entry belongs to. Every log is tied to a single project
            so you can filter by job later.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Date.</strong> Should default to today. If you're catching up from yesterday, backdate
            it — an accurate date beats a wrong one.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Personnel on site.</strong> Who was physically on site for your crew that day. This
            is the "who was there" question you'll be asked in any dispute.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Tag.</strong> One or more classifications — Progress, Issue, Delay, Safety, Delivery,
            Inspection, or General. Tagging takes two seconds and makes a month of entries searchable
            by type in one filter click. If a day had an inspection and a delivery, tag it both.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Notes.</strong> The narrative of the day. What happened, in the order it happened.
            Include weather conditions and how they affected the work — not because there's a dedicated
            weather field, but because weather is the most common basis for schedule extension requests
            and belongs in the written record.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Detail fields (open the entry after creating it)</h2>
        <p>
          These fields live on the log's detail page and capture the substance of the day. Fill them
          in while the day is still fresh.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Work performed.</strong> A description of the specific scope completed — include locations
            (floor, zone, grid line) and quantities where possible. "Rough-in completed, floors 3–5, east
            wing" is more useful than "rough-in." This is what you'll point to when a percent-complete
            question comes up on a pay application.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Materials received.</strong> What arrived on site, with enough detail to connect to
            a delivery ticket if one exists. Useful for tracking stored materials and for disputes about
            when material was available.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Visitors on site.</strong> The GC's superintendent, an owner's representative, the
            building inspector, a delivery driver, a safety officer. Record who came, why they were there,
            and any outcomes (passed inspection, issued a directive, flagged a condition).
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Issues.</strong> Anything that held up the work, changed the scope, or needs follow-up
            — a missing material, an RFI not answered, an unsafe condition corrected, a directive from
            the GC that generates extra cost. If an issue in the log will turn into a <a
              href="/features/change-orders/">change order</a
            >, you can create one directly from the log in BuildWorkPro so the paper trail stays
            connected.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Photos.</strong> Attach images from the field — progress shots, delivery documentation,
            photos of a condition or issue. Photos are tied to the project and date, so the visual record
            sits alongside the written one in the same entry.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Why tagging matters more than you'd think</h2>
        <p>
          When you're writing a log the same day, adding a tag feels like extra work. Six months
          later, when you need to pull every delay entry on a job to support an extension request,
          that two-second step saves hours.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Delay</strong> entries are the basis of schedule extension claims — filter to Delay
            logs and you have a timeline of every day the work was held up and why.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Safety</strong> entries create a documented record if an incident is later questioned.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Inspection</strong> entries capture what was inspected, by whom, and what the result
            was.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Issue</strong> entries are a running log of problems — useful when a GC claims a problem
            was never reported.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          In <a href="/features/site-logs/">site logs</a>, you can filter the timeline or table view
          by project, tag, or reviewed status and search by title or notes. That's how a year of
          daily entries stays navigable instead of becoming an undifferentiated wall of text.
        </p>
      </div>

