      <div
        class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-headings:font-semibold prose-headings:tracking-tight prose-a:text-brand-600"
      >
        <h2>When to write it and who writes it</h2>
        <p>
          The answer to both is the same: the person who was on site, the same day. A field log
          written by someone who wasn't there — or written a week later from memory — loses much of
          its value as a record.
        </p>
        <p>
          In BuildWorkPro, company admins, managers, members, and field crew can all create site
          logs. The Field Crew role is specifically designed for on-site workers: they can write the
          daily record without getting access to bids, pricing, or billing. Make writing the log
          part of the end-of-day routine for whoever closes out the site.
        </p>
        <p>
          Once the crew writes the log, a manager can mark it reviewed — a step that shows the entry
          has been checked and creates a second layer of accountability. Filter by reviewed status
          to find entries that still need a look. Pair site logs with
          <a href="/features/time-tracking/">time tracking</a> to capture crew hours against the same
          project on the same day — the log covers the narrative, time tracking covers the labor record.
        </p>
        <p>
          For the habit side — how to get a crew to keep logs consistently and what makes the
          practice stick — see our guide to
          <a href="/blog/construction-site-log-best-practices/"
            >construction site log best practices</a
          >.
        </p>

        <h2>What not to include</h2>
        <p>
          Daily reports should be factual. Avoid characterizing blame or causation in the log itself
          ("the GC's bad planning caused our delay") — stick to what happened, what you observed,
          and what was communicated. If a directive came verbally from the GC's super, note that a
          verbal directive was given, from whom, about what, and follow up in writing through the
          proper channel. The daily report is a factual record; arguments about responsibility
          belong in formal notices.
        </p>
        <p>
          Also: don't leave gaps. A missing entry for a day where something went wrong is worse than
          a short entry. "Rained all day, no work performed — site flooded east of the utility
          trench" tells the story. A blank day suggests nothing happened or nothing was tracked —
          which is a different problem.
        </p>

        <h2>Connecting daily reports to the rest of the project</h2>
        <p>
          A daily report is more useful when it's connected to the work it documents. In
          BuildWorkPro, each site log lives on the project's own Site Logs tab inside
          <a href="/features/project-management/">project management</a> — so the day's log is one click
          away from the project's tasks, phases, and documents. If an issue documented in a log becomes
          a change order, you can create the change order directly from the log entry, keeping the issue,
          the log, and the resulting change order linked in one place.
        </p>
      </div>

